In '''2009&ndash;10''', '''[[FC Barcelona|Futbol Club Barcelona]]''' started the new season with the prospect of winning six major competitions in the 2009&ndash;2010 season. They contested for the [[2009 Supercopa de EspaÃ±a|Supercopa de EspaÃ±a]], [[2009 UEFA Super Cup|UEFA Super Cup]], [[2009 FIFA Club World Cup|FIFA Club World Cup]], [[2009â10 Copa del Rey|Copa del Rey]], [[La Liga 2009â10|La Liga]], and the [[2009â10 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]]. During the summer transfer window, the club swapped their top league goal scorer during the treble season, [[Samuel Eto'o]] to [[Italy|Italy's]] [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]] in exchange for [[Zlatan IbrahimoviÄ]], along with [[Euro|â¬]]49 million, bringing the total to â¬69 million, which currently makes it second on the [[Transfer (football)#Highest fees|highest transfer fees]] in football history.

On 16 May, Barcelona claimed its 20th league title<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada09-10/05/16/n100516111030.html |title=BarÃ§a 20th League Title |publisher=FCBarcelona.cat |date=2010-05-16 |accessdate=2010-05-17}}</ref> with a record 99 points via a 4&ndash;0 victory over relegated side [[Real Valladolid|Valladolid]] to finish their 2009&ndash;10 season with four titles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada09-10/05/16/n100516111032.html |title=BarÃ§a 4 Titles in 2009/10 |publisher=FCBarcelona.cat |date=2010-05-16 |accessdate=2010-05-17}}</ref>

==Overview==
Over the summer of 2009, along with IbrahimoviÄ, Barcelona reinforced their squad with the signings of [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]] defender [[Maxwell Cabelino Andrade|Maxwell]], [[Brazil]]ian club [[Sociedade Esportiva Palmeiras|Palmeiras]] forward [[Keirrison de Souza Carneiro|Keirrison]] (sent on loan with [[Portugal|Portuguese]] club [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]], then loaned out during the [[transfer window|Winter transfer window]] to Italian side [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]]), and [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] team [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk|Shakhtar Donetsk]] defender [[Dmytro Chygrynskiy]]. Continuing its tradition of using ''[[cantera]]nos'' on the first team, Barcelona manager [[Josep Guardiola]] also promoted four players from the youth reserves, [[Jonathan dos Santos]], [[JeffrÃ©n SuÃ¡rez]], [[Andreu FontÃ s]], and [[Marc Muniesa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada09-10/09/n090901106503.html |title=FCBarcelona.cat |publisher=FCBarcelona.cat |date= |accessdate=2010-03-06}}</ref> Barcelona player [[Henrique Adriano Buss|Henrique]], previously on loan with [[Germany|German]] side [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]], briefly rejoined the squad for the pre-season but was again loaned out, this time to [[Spain|Spanish]] side [[Racing de Santander|Racing Santander]].

==Off the field events==
On 23 September, it was discovered by [[Catalunya|Catalan]] newspaper ''[[El PeriÃ³dico de Catalunya|El PeriÃ³dico]]'' of an investigation into the daily lives of four possible candidates for the Barcelona presidential election in 2010. The investigation was authorized by FC Barcelonaâs director general Joan Oliver, who hired investigating company ''Metodo 3'' to gather daily information on Vice President of Institution and Assets Administration Joan Franquesa, Vice President for Marketing and Media Jaume Ferrer, Vice President for Finance and Treasurer Joan Boix, Vice President for Sport Rafael Yuste between late March and early April 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://translate.google.com/translate?hl=es&sl=es&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.sport.es%2Fdefault.asp%3Fidpublicacio_PK%3D44%26idioma%3DCAS%26idnoticia_PK%3D647815%26idseccio_PK%3D803 |title=Google Traducir |language={{es icon}} |publisher=Translate.google.com |date= |accessdate=2010-03-06}}</ref> Oliver stated in a press conference the next day at the [[Camp Nou]] that "BarÃ§a did no spying but were just protecting the entity of the club."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://translate.google.com/translate?hl=es&sl=es&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.sport.es%2Fdefault.asp%3Fidpublicacio_PK%3D44%26idioma%3DCAS%26idnoticia_PK%3D647562%26idseccio_PK%3D803 |title=Google Traducir |language={{es icon}} |publisher=Translate.google.com |date= |accessdate=2010-03-06}}</ref>

President [[Joan Laporta]] stated that "this happened five months ago. Certain events happened and when I found out about them, the corresponding explanations were given. These explanations were understood and accepted since no law was broken. He added that "it was understood that the reports that were asked for were within the limits of legality and were to protect the affected parties and the club. Therefore, the page was turned and the case was closed." Laporta also said that "we are better than we have ever been in our entire history in our methods of operation, and now, because they want to destabilise us, people drag up issues like these. We will continue the same way, because everyone does it as well. We are used to living under pressure and people trying to destabilise usâ¦ BarÃ§a is united and united we are unbeatable."

Barcelona manager Pep Guardiola stated that "he has shielded the squad from the scandal of the investigation" and that "the subject has not been spoken of in the locker room and even the captains have not mentioned it, there's total concentration."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://translate.google.com/translate?hl=es&sl=es&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.sport.es%2Fdefault.asp%3Fidpublicacio_PK%3D44%26idioma%3DCAS%26idnoticia_PK%3D654142%26idseccio_PK%3D803 |title=Google Traducir |language={{es icon}} |publisher=Translate.google.com |date= |accessdate=2010-03-06}}</ref>

On 11 November, Vice-President Joan Franquesa handed in his resignation for "personal reasons". Continuing the turmoil in the Barcelona Board-Room.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=697407&sec=europe&cc=5901 |title=Barcelona vice-president Joan Franquesa quits board - Europe - ESPN Soccernet |publisher=Soccernet.espn.go.com |date=2009-11-11 |accessdate=2010-03-06}}</ref> President Joan Laporta took action by restructuring the board of directors and making Albert PerrÃ­n, the new Vice-President. Laporta stated "he was making changes for these individuals to get to know the best club better."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://translate.google.com/translate?prev=hp&hl=en&js=y&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.elmundodeportivo.es%2Fgen%2F20091113%2F53823700117%2Fnoticia%2Fsala-i-martin-se-convierte-en-nuevo-tesorero-y-albert-perrin-asciende-a-vicepresidente.html&sl=ca&tl=en&history_state0= |title=Google Translate |publisher=Translate.google.com |date= |accessdate=2010-03-06}}</ref>

===Ballon d'Or & FIFA World Player of the Year===
On 1 December, [[France Football|France Football Magazine]] announced [[Lionel Messi]] was the winner of the [[Ballon d'Or 2009|2009 Ballon d'Or]], thus making him the 9th player while playing at Barcelona and the first Argentine & ''canterano'' from [[La Masia]] to win the coveted footballer prize.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=fr&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.francefootball.fr%2FFF%2Fbreves2009%2F20091201_015505_messi-un-sacre-historique.html |title=Google Translate |publisher=Translate.google.com |date= |accessdate=2010-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/noticies/destacades/n091130108082.html |title=FCBarcelona.cat |publisher=FCBarcelona.cat |date= |accessdate=2010-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada09-10/12/n091130108085.html |title=FCBarcelona.cat |publisher=FCBarcelona.cat |date= |accessdate=2010-03-06}}</ref> Messi dedicated his triumph at the [[Ciutat Esportiva Joan Gamper]] to "my family, who have always been by my side and my teammates at BarÃ§a who've done everything to ensure I could win the award". He also addressed his team-mates [[Xavi HernÃ¡ndez]] and [[AndrÃ©s Iniesta]], who finished third and fourth respectively, "they've given everything for BarÃ§a and they deserve their recognition. If I'd had a vote I would have voted for any of the BarÃ§a players."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada09-10/12/n091201108100.html |title=FCBarcelona.cat |publisher=FCBarcelona.cat |date= |accessdate=2010-03-06}}</ref>

On 21 December, Messi was named [[2009 FIFA World Player of the Year]] at the [[:de:Kongresshaus ZÃ¼rich|Kongresshaus ZÃ¼rich]] in [[ZÃ¼rich]], [[Switzerland]]. Messi claimed the prize by a record vote with a considerable wide margin, receiving 1,073 votes to [[Real Madrid]] [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] 352 votes, who finished second after winning the [[2008 FIFA World Player of the Year|year]] before. Team-mates Xavi and Iniesta finished in third and fifth respectively, closing out 2009 as one of the most memorable years in FC Barcelona history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/noticies/destacades/n091221108480.html |title=FCBarcelona.cat |publisher=FCBarcelona.cat |date=2009-12-21 |accessdate=2010-03-06}}</ref>

On 16 January, Messi became the youngest player to score 100 official goals for the Catalan club. He achieved the feat by scoring a [[brace (sports)|brace]] in a league match vs [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] at the Camp Nou. He stated "It was a relief to get the goal" and "the truth is that with all the big things that have happened to me, well Iâm not giving them too much importance. I just try and live quietly and normally and keep my eye on achieving more." <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada09-10/01/n100117108833.html |title=FCBarcelona.cat |publisher=FCBarcelona.cat |date=2010-01-17 |accessdate=2010-03-06}}</ref>

On 16 May, Messi completed the 2009&ndash;10 as the [[2009â10 La Liga#Pichichi Trophy|Pichichi Throphy]] and the [[European Golden Shoe#1996 to present|European Golden Shoe]] winner with 34 league goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada09-10/05/16/n100516111045.html |title=Messi La Liga Pichichi |publisher=FCBarcelona.cat |date=2010-05-16 |accessdate=2010-05-17}}</ref> While [[VÃ­ctor ValdÃ©s]] won the [[2009â10 La Liga#Zamora Trophy|Zamora Trophy]] for the best La Liga [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] of the season.

===[[International Federation of Football History & Statistics|IFFHS]] Awards===
On 13 January, the International Federation of Football History & Statistic named Xavi HernÃ¡ndez the 2009 Worldâs Best Playmaker and both teammates Lionel Messi and AndrÃ©s Iniesta received second and fourth place respectively. Along with Xavi, manager Pep Guardiola received the World Club Coach 2009. Further increasing the honors received by Barcelona players in 2009.
<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada09-10/01/n100113108761.html |title=FCBarcelona.cat |publisher=FCBarcelona.cat |date=2010-01-13 |accessdate=2010-03-06}}</ref>

==FIFA Club World Cup & season friendly==
On 6 November, director general Joan Oliver confirmed that Barcelona would play a friendly in Kuwait on 21 December against [[Kuwaiti Premier League|Kuwaiti]] club [[Kazma Sporting Club]] at [[Al-Sadaqua Walsalam Stadium]]. It took place after the [[2009 FIFA Club World Cup|FIFA Club World Cup]] which was being hosted in the [[Middle East|same region]] by the [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada09-10/11/n091106107662.html |title=FCBarcelona.cat |publisher=FCBarcelona.cat |date= |accessdate=2010-03-06}}</ref> The match finished 1&ndash;1 with both goals coming in the last 10 minutes of the match in front of a sold out crowd that gathered 45 minutes ahead of the kick-off time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/futbol/temporada_09-10/arxiu_partits/amistosos/kazma_fcb/partit.html |title=FCBarcelona.cat |publisher=FCBarcelona.cat |date= |accessdate=2010-03-06}}</ref> Barcelona received â¬1.7 million to participate in the match.<ref>{{cite web|author=Spain |url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/12/spain/2009/11/06/1608949/barcelona-to-play-lucrative-friendly-against-kazma-sporting-club- |title=Barcelona To Play Lucrative Friendly Against Kazma Sporting Club In December |publisher=Goal.com |date=2009-11-06 |accessdate=2010-03-06}}</ref>

On 16 December, [[Pedro RodrÃ­guez Ledesma|Pedro]] became the first player in history to score in six different club competitions during a single season. He scored in La Liga, Copa del Rey, UEFA Champions League, UEFA Super Cup, Supercopa de EspaÃ±a and the FIFA Club World Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada09-10/12/n091216108378.html |title=FCBarcelona.cat |publisher=FCBarcelona.cat |date=2009-12-16 |accessdate=2010-03-06}}</ref>

On 19 December, Barcelona was crowned FIFA Club World Cup champion with a 1&ndash;2 win over [[Argentina|Argentine]] club [[Estudiantes de La Plata|Estudiantes]] in the [[2009 FIFA Club World Cup Final|final]], making it the sixth title they've won in 2009 and the first club to accomplish that feat within one calendar year known as [[The Sextuple]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/futbol/temporada_09-10/arxiu_partits/mundial_clubs/final/jornada01/Barcelona_estudiantes_lp/partit.html |title=FCBarcelona.cat |publisher=FCBarcelona.cat |date= |accessdate=2010-03-06}}</ref>

